  ================================================================
  STEP 4 — Shor's Algorithm: Recover τ from SRS[1] = τG
  ================================================================

  WHY A SMALL SUBGROUP:
  Full 64-bit curve: N ≈ 2^63 → S=63 → 63+63+63 = 189 qubits
  Statevector RAM   = 2^189 × 16 bytes → physically impossible.
  Small subgroup:   N_sub = 251 (prime) → S=8 → 8+8+8 = 24 qubits
  Statevector RAM   = 2^24 × 16 = 256 MB → safe on any hardware.
  SAME CURVE (CURVE_A, CURVE_B, CURVE_P) — only working N differs.

  Curve           :  y² = x³ + 7800851958821274545x + 3032140762713616321  (mod 12543974025918169487)
  G_sub           :  (9288838633539720391, 2052742288688552359)  (same G as full curve)
  N_sub           :  251  (prime — Shor's subgroup order)
  τ_full          :  4198363722662957428  (full 64-bit secret)
  τ_sub           :  72  = τ_full mod N_sub  (Shor's target)
  Q_sub = τ_sub·G :  (6589249641356245371, 11087473804404518038)  (analogous to SRS[1])

  Qubit budget:
    S (control bits) = ceil(log2(251)) = 8
    Y_BITS           = 8
    Total qubits     = 8+8+8 = 24
    Statevector RAM  = 2^24 × 16 = 268.4 MB

